{"term":"2013","caseName":"BG Group PLC v. Argentina","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/2013/12-138","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - December 02, 2013","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/roberts6/oral_argument_audio/22866","transcript":[{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"We will hear argument next in Case 12-138, BG Group v. The Republic of Argentina.","start":0,"stop":6.587,"duration":6.59},{"text":"Mr. Goldstein.","start":6.587,"stop":7.454,"duration":0.87}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Goldstein","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court:","start":7.454,"stop":10.122,"duration":2.67},{"text":"We ask you to resolve this case narrowly by reaffirming that an arbitrator rather than a court presumptively resolves a dispute over a precondition to arbitration.","start":10.122,"stop":20.328,"duration":10.21},{"text":"That holding would decide the question presented and would resolve the circuit conflict in government 99 percent of the cases in the lower courts.","start":20.328,"stop":27.15,"duration":6.82},{"text":"Argentina wants you to decide a different issue.","start":27.15,"stop":30.202,"duration":3.05},{"text":"Its position in this Court is that there is no arbitration agreement with my client in the first place, so it says a precondition to that non-existent agreement is irrelevant.","start":30.202,"stop":40.741,"duration":10.54},{"text":"Now--","start":40.741,"stop":41.493,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Goldstein, do you take the position that parties can't, by contract say, this particular precondition is -- goes to my -- to the parties' consent to arbitrate?","start":41.493,"stop":55.168,"duration":13.67}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Goldstein","textObjs":[{"text":"--We do not take that position.","start":55.168,"stop":57.02,"duration":1.85},{"text":"If a party were to say that, as the governments in NAFTA have done, as the Solicitor point -- Solicitor General points out is the language of the U.S. South Korea Bilateral Investment Treaty, unlike this one, we think it would be settled that a Court would resolve the dispute.","start":57.02,"stop":72.212,"duration":15.19}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":72.212,"stop":72.646,"duration":0.43},{"text":"So if the issue is what did the parties -- as I see it -- what did the parties intend on this question, why isn't the first options Howsam divide the one that we should follow in this setting?","start":72.646,"stop":90.324,"duration":17.68},{"text":"The Solicitor General is suggesting that we shouldn't follow that.","start":90.324,"stop":94.545,"duration":4.22},{"text":"We should give some sort of heightened deference to the foreign state, but I'm not sure why, because the issue is always about what did the parties intend.","start":94.545,"stop":104.5,"duration":9.95},{"text":"And if the issue is always about that, don't we look at the text?","start":104.5,"stop":109.654,"duration":5.15},{"text":"The custom and practice of the industry?","start":109.654,"stop":112.839,"duration":3.19},{"text":"The behavior between the parties?","start":112.839,"stop":116.308,"duration":3.47},{"text":"Don't we look at all of the factors we normally look at in deciding whether something goes to a substantive or procedural issue?","start":116.308,"stop":126.164,"duration":9.86}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Goldstein","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":126.164,"stop":126.764,"duration":0.6},{"text":"So let me see if I--","start":126.764,"stop":128.033,"duration":1.27}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":128.033,"stop":128.433,"duration":0.4},{"text":"So it's not that we hold absolutely that in every situation a precondition is subject to an arbitral decision.","start":128.433,"stop":137.472,"duration":9.04},{"text":"We look to those -- to the issue of consent, don't we?","start":137.472,"stop":142.042,"duration":4.57}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Goldstein","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, a couple of things about that.","start":142.042,"stop":143.642,"duration":1.6},{"text":"You do -- you have held in Howsam that if there is a precondition to arbitration, it is presumptively decided by the arbitrators rather than the courts, so that--","start":143.642,"stop":152.314,"duration":8.67}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Maybe that's why the government is saying we shouldn't treat it as a presumption.","start":152.314,"stop":155.783,"duration":3.47},{"text":"We should just treat it as--","start":155.783,"stop":157.052,"duration":1.27}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Goldstein","textObjs":[{"text":"--All right.","start":157.052,"stop":158.202,"duration":1.15},{"text":"Maybe I can help by locating the parties' different arguments in this case because there are a lot of them.","start":158.202,"stop":162.522,"duration":4.32},{"text":"We have said, of course, that we think you should decide the question presented.","start":162.522,"stop":165.89,"duration":3.37},{"text":"Argentina wants you to go beyond the question presented, we can talk about whether that's appropriate.","start":165.89,"stop":169.876,"duration":3.99},{"text":"If you did decide the question of consent, I think you would do it in a three-part opinion and some of the parts are contested and some aren't.","start":169.876,"stop":177.865,"duration":7.99},{"text":"This is how I would write the opinion.","start":177.865,"stop":179.348,"duration":1.48},{"text":"Part one would say look at our decision in Howsam and it's undisputed here that if this was an ordinary contract case, just between two American companies, then BG Group would win because this looks just like a procedural precondition.","start":179.348,"stop":193.724,"duration":14.38},{"text":"It's like the John Wiley staged grievance procedure, and I don't think the other side argues against that.","start":193.724,"stop":199.128,"duration":5.4},{"text":"Then the other side has given you two different arguments for why you wouldn't apply Howsam and why you might have a different analytical framework.","start":199.128,"stop":206.715,"duration":7.59},{"text":"The first argument, we could call it part 2 of the opinion, is the argument of the United States.","start":206.715,"stop":212.103,"duration":5.39},{"text":"And what the United States says is look, the difference between this and Howsam is it's an international case.","start":212.103,"stop":217.857,"duration":5.75},{"text":"And what's different in international cases is that when you dealt with Howsam, you dealt with a set of expectations between parties agreeing to arbitrate that may not apply in the international context and so maybe it's different.","start":217.857,"stop":229.83,"duration":11.97},{"text":"Now, this -- and the reason they say that it's different is that an international case, when it's cited in the United States, is governed by the New York Convention.","start":229.83,"stop":238.17,"duration":8.34},{"text":"And in a New York Convention case, whether it's a commercial case, whether it's an international treaty arbitration case, what the rule of judicial review is, and that's what we're looking at here, do the arbitrators finally decide the question or does a court on judicial review decide it?","start":238.17,"stop":253.28,"duration":15.11},{"text":"In a New York Convention case, you look to the law of the citeus.","start":253.28,"stop":257.834,"duration":4.55},{"text":"Here, the United States, the Federal Arbitration Act.","start":257.834,"stop":260.852,"duration":3.02},{"text":"So I take the Solicitor General's position to be this: Look, when you have Argentina arbitrating against a company from the United Kingdom, then the Argentine company and -- excuse me -- Argentina and the UK Company don't have any ex-ante understanding about whether the dispute will be finally resolved by a court or instead the arbitrators because who knows where the arbitration would occur.","start":260.852,"stop":281.949,"duration":21.1},{"text":"Here it occurred in the United States.","start":281.949,"stop":283.449,"duration":1.5},{"text":"Our answer is that this objection answers itself.","start":283.449,"stop":286.919,"duration":3.47},{"text":"It's true that they don't have a specific judicial system, that it will be ahead of time when they sign the treaty.","start":286.919,"stop":293.673,"duration":6.75},{"text":"Argentina signs a treaty with the United Kingdom.","start":293.673,"stop":295.609,"duration":1.94},{"text":"They don't know whether a dispute over this precondition will be resolved de novo or instead, it will be resolved deferentially because they don't know where the arbitration will occur, but they do know that the applicable law will be the citeus of the arbitration.","start":295.609,"stop":310.201,"duration":14.59},{"text":"And there is precedent on this.","start":310.201,"stop":311.918,"duration":1.72},{"text":"The government's argument here is about international arbitration governed by the New York Convention.","start":311.918,"stop":316.788,"duration":4.87},{"text":"There are 149 signatories to the New York Convention.","start":316.788,"stop":320.24,"duration":3.45},{"text":"There have been thousands of challenges to arbitral awards under the New York Convention.","start":320.24,"stop":325.394,"duration":5.15},{"text":"And we are unaware of any precedent from any country ever that says we are going to not apply our domestic system set of rules, here the Howsam first options lines, because this is an international case.","start":325.394,"stop":338.552,"duration":13.16},{"text":"We know that--","start":338.552,"stop":338.902,"duration":0.35}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm not sure that this argument helps you, but it's your argument.","start":338.902,"stop":345.206,"duration":6.3},{"text":"But this arbitration took place in the United States because the parties agreed that's where it would take place, right?","start":345.206,"stop":350.208,"duration":5}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Goldstein","textObjs":[{"text":"--Correct.","start":350.208,"stop":350.61,"duration":0.4}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"So your -- your argument is that by agreeing that the arbitration would take place in the United States, they bought into U.S. arbitration law, no international modification?","start":350.61,"stop":360.981,"duration":10.37}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Goldstein","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":360.981,"stop":361.765,"duration":0.78},{"text":"And that is what has been true in every New York Convention case ever decided in the United States and so far as we are aware, every case decided by every New York Convention signatory because they have -- they are accepting a body of rules.","start":361.765,"stop":373.223,"duration":11.46},{"text":"When you were trying to confirm or overturn the award, they agreed to put it here.","start":373.223,"stop":376.675,"duration":3.45},{"text":"That's how it--","start":376.675,"stop":377.11,"duration":0.44}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"See, I would have thought that there would -- there'd be an argument for saying that the first options principle shouldn't apply to international -- or to a bilateral investment treaty.","start":377.11,"stop":387.216,"duration":10.11},{"text":"The whole point of these treaties, as I understand it, is to take these disputes out of the courts because of distrust, at least of the courts of the country against which the claim is asserted, and -- and put it in an international tribunal where some sort of standard international principles would apply, but that's -- you don't like the idea.","start":387.216,"stop":406.612,"duration":19.4}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Goldstein","textObjs":[{"text":"--No, that's part 3 of the opinion.","start":406.612,"stop":407.646,"duration":1.03},{"text":"I just haven't gotten there.","start":407.646,"stop":408.729,"duration":1.08},{"text":"Here's the reason why, and that is, the government's argument about the New York Convention doesn't have anything to do with investment treaties.","start":408.729,"stop":414.966,"duration":6.24},{"text":"It's about the New York Convention.","start":414.966,"stop":416.402,"duration":1.44},{"text":"And so it applies a company from Japan, chooses a company from Ecuador, and they arbitrate in the United States.","start":416.402,"stop":422.139,"duration":5.74},{"text":"So the government's position has very wide-ranging consequences for any international arbitration in the United States.","start":422.139,"stop":428.376,"duration":6.24},{"text":"Now, Argentina does make the argument that you've described, and this is the next part of the opinion.","start":428.376,"stop":434.364,"duration":5.99},{"text":"If we got past the government's position, which I don't think has any precedent for having a special international rule, we come to Argentina's argument.","start":434.364,"stop":441.783,"duration":7.42},{"text":"And Argentina says this: Look, the reason this isn't Howsam is that this is a unilateral contract, effectively, and that is, we put our treaty out there and now BG Group has to do something in order to create an arbitration agreement in the first place.","start":441.783,"stop":458.062,"duration":16.28},{"text":"Because we don't have an arbitration agreement with them, we have a consented arbitration, then because of that, call it a precondition, call it whatever you want, because an arbitration agreement hasn't formed, the arbitrators have no power to decide anything and, therefore, you can't defer to their judgment.","start":458.062,"stop":475.024,"duration":16.96},{"text":"We would never expect them to have the power to decide anything Argentina says because there's no arbitration agreement at all.","start":475.024,"stop":481.594,"duration":6.57},{"text":"So that's the next part of the opinion, and it will get to the points you raised, Justice Alito.","start":481.594,"stop":485.146,"duration":3.55}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Could I ask you just a -- a practical question and maybe the answer to this is obvious.","start":485.146,"stop":489.183,"duration":4.04},{"text":"Is it too late now for you to begin litigation in Argentina?","start":489.183,"stop":493.902,"duration":4.72},{"text":"Wait 18 months and then pursue arbitration?","start":493.902,"stop":497.804,"duration":3.9}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Goldstein","textObjs":[{"text":"It is not.","start":497.804,"stop":498.72,"duration":0.92},{"text":"There is a principle of latches, but there is an equivalent principle of equitable tolling.","start":498.72,"stop":504.974,"duration":6.25},{"text":"So it's true that we could go there.","start":504.974,"stop":506.743,"duration":1.77},{"text":"I do think ultimately, it's a point in our favor because it shows how pointless this exercise is.","start":506.743,"stop":512.412,"duration":5.67},{"text":"We'll recall, of course, that while we could leave -- we could file a claim in the Argentine courts, the Argentine courts, of course, would have the power to do nothing at all.","start":512.412,"stop":520.667,"duration":8.25},{"text":"They couldn't bind us.","start":520.667,"stop":521.669,"duration":1},{"text":"They couldn't bind Argentina.","start":521.669,"stop":522.985,"duration":1.32},{"text":"They wouldn't have to decide the case in the first place and then we would be back here.","start":522.985,"stop":527.823,"duration":4.84},{"text":"And the question is, if you have a provision like that, which is effectively go wait in the Argentine courts, does anybody seriously think that that determines your consent to arbitrate, when it is that that act, going and sitting, can't have any effect on the case whatsoever.","start":527.823,"stop":542.933,"duration":15.11},{"text":"Do we really--","start":542.933,"stop":543.499,"duration":0.57}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's not true.","start":543.499,"stop":544.499,"duration":1},{"text":"There are numerous statutory regimes where Congress has decided, for example, it's valuable to give people a period of time to negotiate or discuss before you can go into -- into court.","start":544.499,"stop":555.074,"duration":10.57},{"text":"I mean, the EEOC and other sorts of things saying, let's everybody, you know, step back.","start":555.074,"stop":559.794,"duration":4.72},{"text":"You have to negotiate for six months or you can't sue for another eight months.","start":559.794,"stop":563.496,"duration":3.7},{"text":"And a lot of times nobody think that's going to change anything, but you can understand Argentina or any other country saying, look, before we're going to arbitrate, you know, try our courts, you may find -- you may be surprised, right?","start":563.496,"stop":574.402,"duration":10.91}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Goldstein","textObjs":[{"text":"--We would be.","start":574.402,"stop":575.418,"duration":1.02},{"text":"But, Mr. Chief Justice, my point isn't that it's not important.","start":575.418,"stop":579.804,"duration":4.39},{"text":"I'll give them that it's important; they negotiated for it.","start":579.804,"stop":582.087,"duration":2.28},{"text":"My point is that whether it's important or not doesn't tell you if it's a procedural step or a substantive step in terms of their agreeing to arbitrate with us.","start":582.087,"stop":590.61,"duration":8.52}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, then, let me just make clear where we are.","start":590.61,"stop":592.462,"duration":1.85},{"text":"Suppose we, or at least I, were to conclude that the court of appeals was right, that it is for the Judicial Branch to decide whether there is an arbitration agreement and duty to arbitrate.","start":592.462,"stop":608.304,"duration":15.84},{"text":"Then I were to further conclude that, given Argentina's position, they have waived the judicial requirement and that this arbitration should proceed.","start":608.304,"stop":619.529,"duration":11.23},{"text":"I can't reach that second question because it wasn't raised.","start":619.529,"stop":622.231,"duration":2.7}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Goldstein","textObjs":[{"text":"Justice Kennedy, the way you would resolve that issue I believe is to get to Argentina's argument that it did not consent to arbitration, that there is no arbitration agreement in the first place, you would have to go outside the question presented to begin with.","start":622.231,"stop":639.259,"duration":17.03},{"text":"Remember, the question presented that you granted certiorari on to resolve a very distinct circuit conflict at the urging of the arbitration community was: What do we do if we have an arbitration agreement and this is a precondition to arbitration?","start":639.259,"stop":651.75,"duration":12.49},{"text":"If you were going to decide the antecedent question, the question before that, is there an arbitration agreement at all, which is my part three, it is the argument that Argentina is raising in this Court, then I think you have to carry it all the way through.","start":651.75,"stop":663.124,"duration":11.37}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, let me just put it.","start":663.124,"stop":663.807,"duration":0.68},{"text":"I think there is -- this is a close case.","start":663.807,"stop":666.159,"duration":2.35},{"text":"I think there is substantial merit, the United Kingdom court is correct and that the court of appeals here is correct as to the authority of the Court to decide the issue.","start":666.159,"stop":676.532,"duration":10.37},{"text":"I also think that they are probably wrong on the merits, but I cannot reach that second question.","start":676.532,"stop":681.269,"duration":4.74},{"text":"It wasn't presented.","start":681.269,"stop":681.986,"duration":0.72}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Goldstein","textObjs":[{"text":"I agree with you, Justice Kennedy, that if you were asking me did the D.C. Circuit correctly interpret the treaty and decide, I misunderstood you.","start":681.986,"stop":692.726,"duration":10.74},{"text":"You have asked me, look, I see the D.C. Circuit's decision, which is three sentences long on the question of whether they can invoke this waiting period, and I see the arbitrators, they're the experts.","start":692.726,"stop":704.867,"duration":12.14},{"text":"It's much more substantial.","start":704.867,"stop":706.884,"duration":2.02},{"text":"If you accept the United States' argument to remand this case, which neither of the parties think you should, then it could be -- you could suggest to the D.C. Circuit it could reopen it.","start":706.884,"stop":714.888,"duration":8},{"text":"But otherwise I'm going to agree with you, Justice Kennedy.","start":714.888,"stop":716.488,"duration":1.6},{"text":"I am a believer that you should stick with the question presented and the arguments that are properly presented to you.","start":716.488,"stop":721.892,"duration":5.4},{"text":"Let me try, then, to deal with your point ab out the United Kingdom court and the point about how courts decide if there is an arbitration agreement.","start":721.892,"stop":729.146,"duration":7.25},{"text":"We actually agreed that you -- you are obviously a court -- you need to decide if there is an arbitration agreement here.","start":729.146,"stop":735.3,"duration":6.15},{"text":"You do decide that de novo.","start":735.3,"stop":736.734,"duration":1.43},{"text":"The point that I want to get to in the part three of an opinion that I am imagining is that there clearly is an arbitration agreement here, and I am going to come to that in one second.","start":736.734,"stop":746.44,"duration":9.71},{"text":"I will just bracket the point about the United Kingdom.","start":746.44,"stop":748.442,"duration":2},{"text":"Remember that, as I said with the New York convention, the United Kingdom has one system for reviewing arbitral awards, Switzerland has another, we have another one.","start":748.442,"stop":757.731,"duration":9.29},{"text":"What you need to look to I think is your own body of law because each one of those systems is because of not some great principle--","start":757.731,"stop":764.735,"duration":7}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Goldstein, you have given us three parts for an opinion.","start":764.735,"stop":768.189,"duration":3.45}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Goldstein","textObjs":[{"text":"--Yes.","start":768.189,"stop":768.506,"duration":0.32}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Is it your position essentially that under this bilateral agreement, the case is to be decided by an arbitrator, not by a court in Argentina or the United States?","start":768.506,"stop":787.084,"duration":18.58},{"text":"So the question is when an arbitrator will decide the case.","start":787.084,"stop":794.69,"duration":7.61},{"text":"And so the question of when doesn't say whether it's an agreement or not.","start":794.69,"stop":801.26,"duration":6.57},{"text":"It just says, did you sue too early, you started too early?","start":801.26,"stop":808.098,"duration":6.84},{"text":"Is that your essential position, that this bilateral agreement says arbitration is the way this dispute gets decided, and everything on the way to that is what you call a preliminary question, but essentially the parties have agreed that their disputes will be resolved by arbitration?","start":808.098,"stop":830.946,"duration":22.85}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Goldstein","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":830.946,"stop":831.646,"duration":0.7},{"text":"And can I maybe take you to the treaty itself and explain what I think are the questions for courts and what I think are the questions for the arbitrators, because I actually think it's pretty clear from the treaty.","start":831.646,"stop":840.235,"duration":8.59},{"text":"It's in our blue brief in the appendix.","start":840.235,"stop":843.504,"duration":3.27},{"text":"Justice Ginsburg, the answer to your question is yes, and I will explain how that plays out under the treaty.","start":843.504,"stop":848.991,"duration":5.49},{"text":"So this is the agreement that Argentina made with the United Kingdom, and the dispute resolution starts at Page 8A, it's Article VIII.","start":848.991,"stop":857.346,"duration":8.36},{"text":"Now, there are three conditions in this agreement on Argentina's consent to arbitrate.","start":857.346,"stop":865.184,"duration":7.84},{"text":"It does have to agree and we had to do something.","start":865.184,"stop":867.886,"duration":2.7},{"text":"We had to invest.","start":867.886,"stop":868.486,"duration":0.6},{"text":"And those three conditions are set out in the first sentence of the dispute resolution provision.","start":868.486,"stop":873.471,"duration":4.99},{"text":"It says, and I am now on Article VIII, Roman I:","start":873.471,"stop":877.508,"duration":4.04},{"text":"\"Disputes with regard to an investment. \"","start":877.508,"stop":880.544,"duration":3.04},{"text":"so this arbitration provision is only going to apply to an investment, which is a defined term under the treaty,","start":880.544,"stop":885.764,"duration":5.22},{"text":"\"which arises within the terms of the agreement. \"","start":885.764,"stop":888.549,"duration":2.78},{"text":"So it has to be a treaty claim.","start":888.549,"stop":890.482,"duration":1.93},{"text":"\"Between an investor of one contracting party and the other contracting party. \"","start":890.482,"stop":895.719,"duration":5.24},{"text":"So that is it has to be a U.K. investor suing an -- seeking to arbitrate against an Argentine company.","start":895.719,"stop":902.89,"duration":7.17},{"text":"And those are -- if those things aren't true, there is no arbitration agreement.","start":902.89,"stop":907.111,"duration":4.22},{"text":"Now, that, that language I just read to you is from the local litigation provision and then the treaty says the exact same body of disputes are eligible substantively for arbitration.","start":907.111,"stop":918.919,"duration":11.81}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's -- it seems to me that this is a difficulty for you, the structure of the treaty.","start":918.919,"stop":924.556,"duration":5.64},{"text":"I mean, if you just end it after one, nobody would say, oh, they must be contemplating arbitration or arbitration is in the background.","start":924.556,"stop":931.392,"duration":6.84},{"text":"They would say, look, you have got a dispute, if you don't resolve it you bring it in court.","start":931.392,"stop":936.113,"duration":4.72}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Goldstein","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":936.113,"stop":936.529,"duration":0.42}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Nothing about arbitration even in the background.","start":936.529,"stop":938.895,"duration":2.37},{"text":"Then they say: If you want to go to arbitration, you can.","start":938.895,"stop":942.097,"duration":3.2},{"text":"So when you look at just the structure, it seems to suggest that Article I, 8(1) is not part of the arbitration provision.","start":942.097,"stop":950.203,"duration":8.11},{"text":"It stands there and says, this is what you do, and then the arbitration kicks in later.","start":950.203,"stop":954.324,"duration":4.12}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Goldstein","textObjs":[{"text":"I'll agree with that, but I just don't think you can ignore the rest of it.","start":954.324,"stop":957.275,"duration":2.95},{"text":"So let me explain why that's true.","start":957.275,"stop":959.308,"duration":2.03},{"text":"So as I said, those three conditions apply to the arbitration provisions.","start":959.308,"stop":963.429,"duration":4.12},{"text":"So I'm at the top of 9A: “ The aforementioned disputes ” -- those are the ones that meet the three conditions --","start":963.429,"stop":968.831,"duration":5.4},{"text":"\"shall be submitted to international arbitration. \"","start":968.831,"stop":971.2,"duration":2.37},{"text":"And then, Mr. Chief Justice, it turns immediately to the relationship between the local litigation and the arbitration.","start":971.2,"stop":978.122,"duration":6.92},{"text":"It's common ground that in the example that you gave, if you had just part one -- and I just think it's really important by you, Mr. Chief Justice, and that is, if this provision said, go litigate in the local courts come what may, this would be a completely different case.","start":978.122,"stop":992.949,"duration":14.83},{"text":"But this provision is wildly different from that.","start":992.949,"stop":995.651,"duration":2.7},{"text":"It says: Go to the local courts; whatever they do, it makes no difference.","start":995.651,"stop":1000.035,"duration":4.38},{"text":"It cannot stop the case, it can't change the issues that will be arbitrated, it can't have any effect on the arbitrator's decisions.","start":1000.035,"stop":1006.789,"duration":6.75},{"text":"It is exactly like a waiting period, which exists in every international--","start":1006.789,"stop":1012.277,"duration":5.49}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Your argument would be better there if this was Article VIII, you know, arbitration of disputes or, you know, parties can arbitrate but first they must do this.","start":1012.277,"stop":1020.783,"duration":8.51},{"text":"No, it just says settlement of disputes.","start":1020.783,"stop":1023.401,"duration":2.62},{"text":"The first thing is you can go to court here.","start":1023.401,"stop":1025.17,"duration":1.77},{"text":"The second thing is if you want to arbitrate, you do this.","start":1025.17,"stop":1027.953,"duration":2.78}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Goldstein","textObjs":[{"text":"--Okay.","start":1027.953,"stop":1028.119,"duration":0.17},{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, but then I would just take you to the next page, sub 4.","start":1028.119,"stop":1032.438,"duration":4.32},{"text":"And we understand what the answer to that ambiguity perhaps is, the last sentence:","start":1032.438,"stop":1037.392,"duration":4.95},{"text":"\"The arbitration decision shall be final and binding on both parties. \"","start":1037.392,"stop":1041.527,"duration":4.13},{"text":"That is the only body under this treaty that can issue a decision that decides the parties' dispute.","start":1041.527,"stop":1046.765,"duration":5.24},{"text":"It's only the arbitrators.","start":1046.765,"stop":1048.381,"duration":1.62},{"text":"Now--","start":1048.381,"stop":1049.049,"duration":0.67}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"If you want to accept the invitation to arbitrate that is in 8(2).","start":1049.049,"stop":1053.084,"duration":4.04},{"text":"If you don't, if you go to 8(1), which doesn't say anything, then presumably the decision of the tribunal will be binding.","start":1053.084,"stop":1059.338,"duration":6.25}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Goldstein","textObjs":[{"text":"--Fair enough -- no, that's not quite right, Mr. Chief Justice, because remember, imagine that we went to the Argentine courts and for the first time ever we won.","start":1059.338,"stop":1069.28,"duration":9.94},{"text":"So that an Argentine court told the Argentine state: You know, we actually think you should pay this company $200 million.","start":1069.28,"stop":1076.2,"duration":6.92},{"text":"What would happen then is that Argentina can take the question to arbitration.","start":1076.2,"stop":1080.419,"duration":4.22},{"text":"But nothing about the local court's decision binds anyone.","start":1080.419,"stop":1084.806,"duration":4.39},{"text":"There is never a point at which you can say that the investor will abide by or be bound by a decision of an Argentine court under this system.","start":1084.806,"stop":1094.428,"duration":9.62},{"text":"That's what's so unusual about it.","start":1094.428,"stop":1095.962,"duration":1.53},{"text":"Perhaps I can explain why it's there, because it is odd, I will tell you, and I will tell you that in deciding this question that Argentina is adding to the case in the context of this local litigation provision, it is a very strange vehicle to do that.","start":1095.962,"stop":1109.954,"duration":13.99},{"text":"There are only 1 percent of bilateral investment treaties have this provision.","start":1109.954,"stop":1114.408,"duration":4.45},{"text":"It's a historic remnant.","start":1114.408,"stop":1116.658,"duration":2.25},{"text":"It's in -- of the first 15 bilateral investment treaties that Argentina agreed to, it's in 9 of them.","start":1116.658,"stop":1123.112,"duration":6.45},{"text":"In the subsequent 40 of them, it doesn't appear at all.","start":1123.112,"stop":1126.649,"duration":3.54},{"text":"Again, a good example of how it isn't really a condition on their consent.","start":1126.649,"stop":1130.018,"duration":3.37},{"text":"And it is a remnant of an era of espousal.","start":1130.018,"stop":1133.303,"duration":3.29},{"text":"It used to be the case that before these treaties that an investor in BG's position would have to go to the Argentine courts, and when Argentina first created the investment treaties, it kind of liked the idea that you had to spend some time in the courts.","start":1133.303,"stop":1146.545,"duration":13.24},{"text":"But no one would agree to the treaty -- this is Justice Alito's question earlier.","start":1146.545,"stop":1150.764,"duration":4.22},{"text":"No one would ever agree to these treaties if they didn't know that the decisionmaker would be the neutral, expert arbitrators, and so it just has this you-have-to-wait-in-court feel to it.","start":1150.764,"stop":1160.554,"duration":9.79},{"text":"But it is absolutely critical that we look at the substance of the provision.","start":1160.554,"stop":1164.439,"duration":3.88},{"text":"It's very much, Mr. Chief Justice, like the John Wiley case, which is structured: One, you will have step one of our grievance process; step two, within five days you have to go to our next step of the grievance process; step three, then you can go on to arbitration.","start":1164.439,"stop":1177.499,"duration":13.06},{"text":"It could have stopped, theoretically, at any of those.","start":1177.499,"stop":1179.618,"duration":2.12},{"text":"If you had given up at step one or two, you would well have been bound by it.","start":1179.618,"stop":1183.486,"duration":3.87},{"text":"But the question you are being asked here, if we could just return to if you are trying to decide this de novo or instead defer to the arbitrators' interpretation of whether this litigation provision is binding, is fundamentally when Argentina went into this treaty did it think that the arbitrators were going to resolve the disputes?","start":1183.486,"stop":1203.566,"duration":20.08},{"text":"Right?","start":1203.566,"stop":1204.199,"duration":0.63},{"text":"Did it expect -- it's a question of consent, Justice Sotomayor -- did it expect that the answers to these questions would come from the arbitrators or instead the courts?","start":1204.199,"stop":1212.172,"duration":7.97},{"text":"And when we are talking about the process for getting it going -- Justice Ginsburg talked about the timing, do you have to do this for 18 months, there is another provision here about 3 months.","start":1212.172,"stop":1221.778,"duration":9.61},{"text":"The natural understanding is that there is an arbitration agreement.","start":1221.778,"stop":1224.98,"duration":3.2},{"text":"Argentina knew that it could only get this treaty if there was a guarantee to the investors that they would be able to arbitrate, and so expects the arbitrators to decide this.","start":1224.98,"stop":1234.085,"duration":9.11},{"text":"Imagine Argentina's world, if you will.","start":1234.085,"stop":1236.285,"duration":2.2},{"text":"Argentina's world is that every timing question, whether something has to be filed on blue paper -- I have no idea what the line they want to draw is.","start":1236.285,"stop":1245.141,"duration":8.86},{"text":"Every procedural step is instead a condition on its consent to arbitrate.","start":1245.141,"stop":1250.528,"duration":5.39},{"text":"And that doesn't seem to make any sense at all.","start":1250.528,"stop":1252.98,"duration":2.45},{"text":"There have to be procedural prerequisites.","start":1252.98,"stop":1254.748,"duration":1.77},{"text":"And Argentina would recharacterize this as, as I said, a unilateral agreement.","start":1254.748,"stop":1259.733,"duration":4.98},{"text":"So it's like Argentina says -- posts a sign on a pole and says if you pay me -- if you find my dog I will give you $100.","start":1259.733,"stop":1267.739,"duration":8.01},{"text":"And so you have to perform an act.","start":1267.739,"stop":1269.389,"duration":1.65},{"text":"And it says we have to perform an act here.","start":1269.389,"stop":1271.474,"duration":2.09},{"text":"We have to go to the local courts or otherwise there is no agreement at all.","start":1271.474,"stop":1275.578,"duration":4.1},{"text":"Well, a few things about that.","start":1275.578,"stop":1277.462,"duration":1.88},{"text":"Arbitration is not a dog, and Article 8, if we just go back to page 8A, does not require us to submit it to the local courts at all.","start":1277.462,"stop":1286.468,"duration":9.01},{"text":"This can't be a step that we are required to take because we are not required to take it.","start":1286.468,"stop":1291.172,"duration":4.7},{"text":"If I could just take you to the last two lines of it.","start":1291.172,"stop":1293.64,"duration":2.47},{"text":"It shall be submitted at the request of one of the parties to the dispute.","start":1293.64,"stop":1298.341,"duration":4.7},{"text":"Argentina was just as entitled as us to put this into the local courts as we were.","start":1298.341,"stop":1303.929,"duration":5.59},{"text":"It can't have been an expectation that we had to do something before it would consent to arbitration.","start":1303.929,"stop":1309.666,"duration":5.74},{"text":"So I do think that this is just on all fours with John Wiley for that, for that reason.","start":1309.666,"stop":1315.47,"duration":5.8},{"text":"The only other thing that has been put on the table in front of you is the question of whether Argentina's sovereignty should make a difference here.","start":1315.47,"stop":1322.893,"duration":7.42},{"text":"And this is kind of the second theme of the brief of the United States.","start":1322.893,"stop":1327.111,"duration":4.22},{"text":"And I would say about that that the Foreign Sovereign Immunities Act, which was discussed of course in the last argument, has an express waiver of sovereign immunity for arbitration awards that's controlled here.","start":1327.111,"stop":1338.085,"duration":10.97},{"text":"And if, when the Solicitor General's representative speaks, if that person were to talk about what the treatment of these issues in other countries is, we are unaware again of any country in the world where the arbitral system of review in the courts changes in the slightest because one party happens to be a signatory to a treaty, and that makes a ton of sense.","start":1338.085,"stop":1360.099,"duration":22.01},{"text":"Again, this is fundamentally a commercial relationship.","start":1360.099,"stop":1362.884,"duration":2.79},{"text":"Argentina knew that it couldn't, in the crisis that gave rise to these investment treaties, Argentina couldn't get the money to come into the country if it hadn't agreed to arbitration.","start":1362.884,"stop":1371.974,"duration":9.09}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"--Counsel, what do you do with Wintershall?","start":1371.974,"stop":1374.592,"duration":2.62}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Goldstein","textObjs":[{"text":"So, Your Honor, I think that there are a variety of cases out there that deal with the question in other jurisdictions of different ways of reviewing arbitration awards.","start":1374.592,"stop":1387.585,"duration":12.99},{"text":"And those are unique to their own arbitral system.","start":1387.585,"stop":1391.553,"duration":3.97},{"text":"We've cited decisions from -- a decision from France, for example, that follows your Howsam line.","start":1391.553,"stop":1396.372,"duration":4.82},{"text":"The important point I would make is that there is -- when the other side points to decisions in which a court reviews de novo a jurisdictional ruling of an arbitral tribunal, none of those decisions are unique in any way to the fact that it was an international arbitration or an international treaty arbitration.","start":1396.372,"stop":1415.752,"duration":19.38},{"text":"Their international rule, the U.K. rule, the rule in lots of other countries, is simply about arbitration.","start":1415.752,"stop":1421.239,"duration":5.49},{"text":"The reason that the other side can say that this case might well be reviewed de novo in the United Kingdom, for example, is that the jurisdictional decision in essentially every arbitration of any kind in the United Kingdom will be reviewed de novo.","start":1421.239,"stop":1434.899,"duration":13.66},{"text":"They just have a different approach to these questions.","start":1434.899,"stop":1436.765,"duration":1.87}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Isn't that the same thing in France, which is supposed to be a popular place for international arbitration, that in the first instance the arbitrator decides, but ultimately the court can review everything?","start":1436.765,"stop":1449.909,"duration":13.14}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Goldstein","textObjs":[{"text":"That is not the most current view, Justice Ginsburg.","start":1449.909,"stop":1452.944,"duration":3.03},{"text":"In a case called Nihon Plast, which was the most recent court of appeals decision in France in 2004, the court adopted the procedural-substantive distinction that very much parallels Justice Breyer's opinion in the Howsam case.","start":1452.944,"stop":1468.637,"duration":15.69},{"text":"But even if it were the case, it's because the French have their own approach to arbitration.","start":1468.637,"stop":1473.607,"duration":4.97},{"text":"We have a system that says, look, if you can always run off to court because of any of these procedural objections -- it has to be on blue paper, you didn't write -- wait for the -- wait 30 days.","start":1473.607,"stop":1482.796,"duration":9.19},{"text":"Another great example would be in lots of arbitration provisions you have to submit a sufficiently detailed statement of claim to the arbitrators.","start":1482.796,"stop":1490.65,"duration":7.85},{"text":"Well, that would be--","start":1490.65,"stop":1491.486,"duration":0.84}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"Do I understand your position that in this case you did not have to go to the Federal -- to the Argentine court by reason of the language in this agreement and not by reason of anything that Argentina did?","start":1491.486,"stop":1506.079,"duration":14.59}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Goldstein","textObjs":[{"text":"--The language in the agreement meant that what Argentina did disentitled it from being able to rely on this provision.","start":1506.079,"stop":1514.332,"duration":8.25},{"text":"I will take you quickly, if you don't mind, to the provisions of the treaty so you know what I am talking about.","start":1514.332,"stop":1518.569,"duration":4.24},{"text":"There are two of them.","start":1518.569,"stop":1519.686,"duration":1.12},{"text":"One is the one that the arbitrators relied on, and that is in the arbitration provision 8-4, which is on 10A, says:","start":1519.686,"stop":1529.058,"duration":9.37},{"text":"\"The arbitral tribunal shall decide the dispute in accordance with the provisions of this agreement, the laws of the contracting party involved in the dispute, including conflict of laws. \"","start":1529.058,"stop":1537.748,"duration":8.69},{"text":"and then at the end of the sentence,","start":1537.748,"stop":1539.231,"duration":1.48},{"text":"\"the applicable principles of international law. \"","start":1539.231,"stop":1541.099,"duration":1.87},{"text":"So this exhaustion requirement -- it's not even an exhaustion requirement -- the local litigation requirement is subject to international law.","start":1541.099,"stop":1547.186,"duration":6.09},{"text":"And then earlier -- and so three other tribunals have reached the same conclusion as this one, that you, for that reason of that provision, you can't rely in the particular circumstances on the local litigation.","start":1547.186,"stop":1558.477,"duration":11.29},{"text":"And then Article III--","start":1558.477,"stop":1559.744,"duration":1.27}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Say that again.","start":1559.744,"stop":1561.513,"duration":1.77}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Goldstein","textObjs":[{"text":"--Sorry.","start":1561.513,"stop":1561.996,"duration":0.48}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"By reason of--","start":1561.996,"stop":1563.113,"duration":1.12}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Goldstein","textObjs":[{"text":"There are three other tribunals--","start":1563.113,"stop":1564.148,"duration":1.03}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"--Yes.","start":1564.148,"stop":1564.665,"duration":0.52}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Goldstein","textObjs":[{"text":"--that have reached the same conclusion as this one.","start":1564.665,"stop":1566.281,"duration":1.62},{"text":"And that is Argentina can't rely on the local litigation provision because it effectively closed the courthouse doors.","start":1566.281,"stop":1572.987,"duration":6.71},{"text":"It's own conduct disentitled it.","start":1572.987,"stop":1574.771,"duration":1.78},{"text":"Then ten other tribunals have reached the same conclusion based on Article III, the most favored nation provision, because this requirement doesn't exist in the Argentina-U.","start":1574.771,"stop":1585.044,"duration":10.27},{"text":"S. BIT.","start":1585.044,"stop":1585.644,"duration":0.6},{"text":"There are only three tribunals -- to be clear, only three tribunals out of 16 or 17 have agreed to enforce it.","start":1585.644,"stop":1592.298,"duration":6.65},{"text":"If I could reserve the remainder of my time.","start":1592.298,"stop":1594.066,"duration":1.77}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, counsel.","start":1594.066,"stop":1594.766,"duration":0.7},{"text":"Ms. Anders.","start":1594.766,"stop":1602.504,"duration":7.74}]},{"speakerName":"Ginger D. Anders","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court:","start":1602.504,"stop":1604.872,"duration":2.37},{"text":"The government's position in this case is based on the fact that this case involves a bilateral investment treaty in which the state parties set forth a standing offer to arbitrate in the treaty itself.","start":1604.872,"stop":1616.163,"duration":11.29},{"text":"Because it's the treaty that determines whether there is an arbitration agreement in this case, principles of treaty interpretation have to be used to assess whether there is an agreement.","start":1616.163,"stop":1625.185,"duration":9.02},{"text":"So therefore, applying the domestic law presumptions that are set forth in Howsam to this type of investor-state arbitration we think would not be appropriate.","start":1625.185,"stop":1634.041,"duration":8.86},{"text":"Howsam shouldn't apply by its terms because the question here is a question of treaty interpretation, not a question of the likely expectations of parties to a domestic commercial contract.","start":1634.041,"stop":1643.081,"duration":9.04}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"I must say I don't follow that line of argument.","start":1643.081,"stop":1646.966,"duration":3.88},{"text":"I mean, it seems to me the treaty sets the framework for an agreement, but it is ultimately the agreement that governs.","start":1646.966,"stop":1655.204,"duration":8.24}]},{"speakerName":"Ginger D. Anders","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, there is no agreement unless the investor submits the claim to arbitration in accordance with the terms of the treaty, the conditions on the state's consent.","start":1655.204,"stop":1665.762,"duration":10.56},{"text":"So, for instance, in the United States investment treaties and free trade agreements such as NAFTA the United States says that an investor may submit a claim to arbitration only if it first satisfies certainly procedural conditions.","start":1665.762,"stop":1678.154,"duration":12.39}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't -- I can't find -- it seems to me this has sprung, full blown, from someone's brain, but is not well embedded in any law that I could yet find.","start":1678.154,"stop":1691.227,"duration":13.07},{"text":"That is the -- this is not meant to be rude.","start":1691.227,"stop":1694.848,"duration":3.62},{"text":"I'm trying to figure out where this idea of the consent thing comes from.","start":1694.848,"stop":1698.983,"duration":4.13},{"text":"After all, it apparently comes from our Korean treaty and maybe one other, but I can't find it in -- I can't find -- the question in the case is, is this particular agreement, namely an agreement to go to the court first -- shall we count it as that kind of matter as to whether this is arbitrable that goes to a judge?","start":1698.983,"stop":1722.266,"duration":23.28},{"text":"Or rather is it that kind of procedural Howsam, Wiley type thing that goes to an arbitrator.","start":1722.266,"stop":1729.186,"duration":6.92},{"text":"Now, we did our best I think to try to explain how to distinguish the one from the other in our precedent.","start":1729.186,"stop":1736.858,"duration":7.67},{"text":"Now, you use different words.","start":1736.858,"stop":1739.544,"duration":2.69},{"text":"You use these words about “ consent ”, which doesn't appear anywhere in this treaty, but I think you are trying to get at the same thing.","start":1739.544,"stop":1749.25,"duration":9.71},{"text":"And if you are not trying to get at the same thing, why?","start":1749.25,"stop":1752.718,"duration":3.47},{"text":"Why not?","start":1752.718,"stop":1753.804,"duration":1.09},{"text":"What are you trying to get at?","start":1753.804,"stop":1754.97,"duration":1.17}]},{"speakerName":"Ginger D. Anders","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think the reason that applying Howsam and its presumption that certain procedural-type requirements like notice requirements would be decided by the arbitrator, the reason that would risk subjecting a state to suit without its consent is that in investment treaties, what the states do is they say we will be subject to arbitration under certain circumstances.","start":1754.97,"stop":1775.233,"duration":20.26},{"text":"But they also place limitations on their consent to that adjudication in order to satisfy important sovereign--","start":1775.233,"stop":1781.721,"duration":6.49}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Are you suggesting that they--","start":1781.721,"stop":1782.906,"duration":1.18}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"So you suggest it was the State that said, Look, they don't say anything in the treaty, but it turns out, for purposes of counting time limits, filing a brief, they count Saturdays, but they don't count Sundays.","start":1782.906,"stop":1796.081,"duration":13.17},{"text":"All right?","start":1796.081,"stop":1797.281,"duration":1.2},{"text":"And the government says, quite sincerely: If we had known that they were going to do that, we never would have agreed.","start":1797.281,"stop":1805.087,"duration":7.81},{"text":"I am trying to get an example of something that is as purely procedural as I can imagine, something no one in his right mind would think a judge, rather than an arbitrator, should decide.","start":1805.087,"stop":1815.644,"duration":10.56},{"text":"But under your rule, you're going to say the judges decide that and not the arbitrators, and that is what is bothering me about your rule.","start":1815.644,"stop":1823.981,"duration":8.34}]},{"speakerName":"Ginger D. Anders","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, they decided them because the state sets forth in the treaty itself that these are limitations on their consent.","start":1823.981,"stop":1829.052,"duration":5.07}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"By the way, in the treaty itself, you can have dozens of things, as was true of Howsam.","start":1829.052,"stop":1834.689,"duration":5.64},{"text":"We will follow the UNCTAD, whatever that is, the UN or AAA rules, and you look up AAA Rule No. 1872(b) and it says just what I said.","start":1834.689,"stop":1846.18,"duration":11.49},{"text":"Okay?","start":1846.18,"stop":1846.73,"duration":0.55},{"text":"So now it's in the treaty itself, and why should that matter?","start":1846.73,"stop":1850.282,"duration":3.55}]},{"speakerName":"Ginger D. Anders","textObjs":[{"text":"Because, for instance, what the United States has done in negotiating its treaties and free trade agreements for decades, in every one of these agreements is it has said: We need to limit the circumstances in which we.","start":1850.282,"stop":1862.106,"duration":11.82}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"I have only found two, by the way.","start":1862.106,"stop":1863.458,"duration":1.35},{"text":"One was Korea and I can't remember the second.","start":1863.458,"stop":1866.41,"duration":2.95}]},{"speakerName":"Ginger D. Anders","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we cited in our brief the Korea and--","start":1866.41,"stop":1868.16,"duration":1.75}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"But in any case--","start":1868.16,"stop":1868.679,"duration":0.52}]},{"speakerName":"Ginger D. Anders","textObjs":[{"text":"--and NAFTA.","start":1868.679,"stop":1869.262,"duration":0.58}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"--you explicitly say, these are our conditions of consent, and you raise the question to me, you don't answer it.","start":1869.262,"stop":1876.033,"duration":6.77},{"text":"Because suppose one of those conditions had to do with blue paper rather than white paper.","start":1876.033,"stop":1880.151,"duration":4.12},{"text":"Suppose that they were just what I said.","start":1880.151,"stop":1881.92,"duration":1.77},{"text":"Nobody still would think the United States was resisting arbitration on such a matter.","start":1881.92,"stop":1886.557,"duration":4.64}]},{"speakerName":"Ginger D. Anders","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, to give you an example of a condition that we've actually used, NAFTA requires as a condition on the United States' consent to arbitrate that the investors, when they submit the claim to arbitration, they waive their right to pursue other remedies, and that satisfies a very important sovereign interests that we have and not being subject to parallel proceedings--","start":1886.557,"stop":1904.785,"duration":18.23}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"So here you are putting yourselves, I gather, that the U.N. rules, the AAA rules, the scholars who file our briefs, the doctrine of competence-competence, whatever that might be, is in fact far broader than what they want.","start":1904.785,"stop":1917.093,"duration":12.31},{"text":"It submits virtually every question of arbitrability to the arbitrator.","start":1917.093,"stop":1921.228,"duration":4.13},{"text":"And the United States is taking a position quite contrary, I guess, to most of the world.","start":1921.228,"stop":1925.766,"duration":4.54}]},{"speakerName":"Ginger D. Anders","textObjs":[{"text":"--I don't think that's correct, Justice Breyer.","start":1925.766,"stop":1927.968,"duration":2.2},{"text":"What we are -- what we are saying is that when a position goes to consent whether it is fulfilled or not goes to whether--","start":1927.968,"stop":1933.787,"duration":5.82}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"How do we know that?","start":1933.787,"stop":1934.754,"duration":0.97},{"text":"The question is: Is this litigation preliminary, going to the Argentinian court, is the litigation preliminary a condition on the consent to arbitrate a dispute?","start":1934.754,"stop":1951.833,"duration":17.08},{"text":"What is the answer to that question in the view of the United States?","start":1951.833,"stop":1955.118,"duration":3.28}]},{"speakerName":"Ginger D. Anders","textObjs":[{"text":"--That's a question of treaty interpretation and this Court has said that you look to first the text, but you also--","start":1955.118,"stop":1961.889,"duration":6.77}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, let's say you've done all that.","start":1961.889,"stop":1963.141,"duration":1.25},{"text":"And what does the United States -- the United States is saying: Court, you should look to all these sources, and then answer the question: Is the litigation preliminary a condition on consent to arbitrate the dispute?","start":1963.141,"stop":1977.748,"duration":14.61},{"text":"So after looking at the sources that the United States is telling the Court it should look to, what is the answer of the United States to that question?","start":1977.748,"stop":1987.339,"duration":9.59}]},{"speakerName":"Ginger D. Anders","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, the United States doesn't feel that it is appropriate for it to express a definitive view on that question now because the parties have not argued this really as a question--","start":1987.339,"stop":1996.112,"duration":8.77}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"I would be more open about that argument, Ms. Anders, if you had at least suggested how we should go about deciding that question?","start":1996.112,"stop":2003.449,"duration":7.34}]},{"speakerName":"Ginger D. Anders","textObjs":[{"text":"--Yes.","start":2003.449,"stop":2003.816,"duration":0.37}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"Because you read this through your brief, and I don't know what a consent-based objection is.","start":2003.816,"stop":2010.372,"duration":6.56},{"text":"In fact, you say consent-based objections can look very, very procedural and it's still consent-based, or it might not be consent-based.","start":2010.372,"stop":2018.975,"duration":8.6},{"text":"So all the techniques that we use in the Howsam-First Options line of cases seem to go out the window and not be replaced with anything else.","start":2018.975,"stop":2029.166,"duration":10.19}]},{"speakerName":"Ginger D. Anders","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't think that's right.","start":2029.166,"stop":2031.701,"duration":2.54},{"text":"I think what you look to, just looking at the text, you can look to whether the text expressly calls something a condition on consent.","start":2031.701,"stop":2039.555,"duration":7.85},{"text":"So, for instance, in NAFTA, NAFTA says that there are certain conditions--","start":2039.555,"stop":2044.193,"duration":4.64}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"That's no different from the rules we apply when there isn't a treaty, of course.","start":2044.193,"stop":2048.578,"duration":4.38},{"text":"I mean, if the arbitration agreement said that, that the -- you know, the agreement is conditioned on, of course.","start":2048.578,"stop":2055.233,"duration":6.66},{"text":"So what else?","start":2055.233,"stop":2056.05,"duration":0.82},{"text":"What different rules would you apply other than the common sense rules that we use for arbitration agreements?","start":2056.05,"stop":2064.522,"duration":8.47}]},{"speakerName":"Ginger D. Anders","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, you would also -- you would also look possibly for mandatory language in the treaty; so, for instance, if the treaty says that--","start":2064.522,"stop":2070.176,"duration":5.65}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"We would look to mandatory language in the arbitration agreement.","start":2070.176,"stop":2073.045,"duration":2.87}]},{"speakerName":"Ginger D. Anders","textObjs":[{"text":"--I think that's right, but the problem with applying Howsam is that it's a presumption that is purely based on the nature of the requirement, so the fact that it is a notice requirement, the fact that it is a time limit, that that means that it's procedural and, therefore, the arbitrators would decide unless it is clearly stated--","start":2073.045,"stop":2088.138,"duration":15.09}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"What about this -- what about this principle.","start":2088.138,"stop":2088.938,"duration":0.8},{"text":"If something, if some requirement seems to serve virtually no purpose, it's unlikely to be a condition of consent; would you accept that?","start":2088.938,"stop":2097.927,"duration":8.99}]},{"speakerName":"Ginger D. Anders","textObjs":[{"text":"--No, I think that is still -- that would be grafting on a default term onto the treaty that may not reflect the treaty parties' intent.","start":2097.927,"stop":2104.833,"duration":6.91},{"text":"I think when states negotiate for these conditions on consent, what they are looking to are--","start":2104.833,"stop":2108.718,"duration":3.88}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, there is nothing in the treaty that talks about consent at all, so we have to decide whether some requirement is a consent, is on something which consent is conditioned, or it's just a procedural requirement that would be decided by an arbitrator.","start":2108.718,"stop":2122.711,"duration":13.99},{"text":"Would you not -- would you disagree with the proposition that if something really is trivial, it doesn't seem to accomplish much of anything.","start":2122.711,"stop":2129.449,"duration":6.74},{"text":"It's a historical vestige.","start":2129.449,"stop":2131.232,"duration":1.78},{"text":"It's unlikely to be a condition of consent.","start":2131.232,"stop":2133.617,"duration":2.39}]},{"speakerName":"Ginger D. Anders","textObjs":[{"text":"--I think one of the things the Court could look to is the nature of the requirements, does it serve sovereign functions, but I think in doing that analysis it's important to look to what the state says are the functions that its requirements are serving.","start":2133.617,"stop":2145.241,"duration":11.62},{"text":"So for instance, our notice requirement in our treaties, they serve the purpose of giving us advance notice of particular claims and time to correct problems that may have been caused that we can correct and, therefore, avoid arbitration to begin with.","start":2145.241,"stop":2158.218,"duration":12.98},{"text":"So I think you would look to the nature of the requirement, the text of the treaty, whether it's mandatory or whether it's expressly conditional.","start":2158.218,"stop":2164.305,"duration":6.09},{"text":"You can also look, obviously, to what this Court has called its interpretation, so that would be the postratification understanding.","start":2164.305,"stop":2170.959,"duration":6.65},{"text":"If this were our treaty, we would bring in, you know, the letter of transmittal that the State Department had provided after it had negotiated the treaty.","start":2170.959,"stop":2179.814,"duration":8.86},{"text":"You know, there would be a lot of information like that that a Court could look to.","start":2179.814,"stop":2183.182,"duration":3.37},{"text":"And I think as the Court noted in the Sumitomo case, you can have similar language in similar treaties that have different meaning because there is different negotiating history or the aids to interpretation point different ways.","start":2183.182,"stop":2194.99,"duration":11.81},{"text":"So our point here is that it's a matter of treaty interpretation and that you simply have to look to the--","start":2194.99,"stop":2199.376,"duration":4.39}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"What's wrong with the House -- and I'm being a little defensive here -- but I didn't think there was the presumption you are talking.","start":2199.376,"stop":2205.363,"duration":5.99},{"text":"I thought it said there's a presumption about that procedural rule, and I thought important language was the language that the Court has found the phrase, i.e., for the judge applicable in the narrow circumstance where contracting parties would likely have expected a Court to have decided the gateway matter.","start":2205.363,"stop":2221.989,"duration":16.63},{"text":"Now, that, it seems to me, a little bit easier to work with then this notion of whether a state gave consent or didn't give consent or it doesn't mention it in treaty.","start":2221.989,"stop":2229.995,"duration":8.01}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Briefly.","start":2229.995,"stop":2232.528,"duration":2.53}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you.","start":2232.528,"stop":2233.363,"duration":0.84}]},{"speakerName":"Ginger D. Anders","textObjs":[{"text":"--I think in the treaty context, the state's parties are not agreeing, and they don't have expectations with respect to the allocation of authority between the court and the arbitrator.","start":2233.363,"stop":2241.134,"duration":7.77},{"text":"What they do agree to are conditions on consent that limit the terms on which the state may be subject to arbitration.","start":2241.134,"stop":2246.105,"duration":4.97}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, counsel.","start":2246.105,"stop":2247.89,"duration":1.78},{"text":"Mr. Blackman?","start":2247.89,"stop":2253.943,"duration":6.05}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan I. Blackman","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice and May it please the Court: This is a contract formation case and it's a case that is decided properly by the court below whether you apply first options or whether you apply treaty principles.","start":2253.943,"stop":2267.268,"duration":13.32}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Blackman, may I ask you preliminarily, on your view, what happens next.","start":2267.268,"stop":2274.44,"duration":7.17},{"text":"Can this party -- and suppose you're right -- can the BG Group institute an action in Argentina and if it's not resolved within 18 months invoke arbitration?","start":2274.44,"stop":2293.418,"duration":18.98}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan I. Blackman","textObjs":[{"text":"Absolutely, yes.","start":2293.418,"stop":2294.618,"duration":1.2},{"text":"And my friend conceded that.","start":2294.618,"stop":2296.37,"duration":1.75},{"text":"There is no barrier.","start":2296.37,"stop":2297.57,"duration":1.2}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"And if it is resolved, but not to BG's liking then, thereto, BG can invoke arbitration.","start":2297.57,"stop":2305.743,"duration":8.17}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan I. Blackman","textObjs":[{"text":"That's absolutely correct, Your Honor.","start":2305.743,"stop":2307.328,"duration":1.59}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, doesn't that mean that treaty partners agreed that only an arbitration panel can conclusively resolve this dispute?","start":2307.328,"stop":2315.767,"duration":8.44}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan I. Blackman","textObjs":[{"text":"What the treaty partners agreed to here, Justice Ginsburg, was a condition, a precondition on their respectively derogating from their sovereignty.","start":2315.767,"stop":2326.823,"duration":11.06},{"text":"Absent the bilateral investment treaty, there is no basis on which an investor could ever compel one of these states to arbitrate its claims, and its only remedy would lie in the courts of that state.","start":2326.823,"stop":2340.066,"duration":13.24}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't get your answer to my question.","start":2340.066,"stop":2342.934,"duration":2.87},{"text":"Am I wrong in thinking that under this treaty, the ultimate decisionmaker is the arbitrator.","start":2342.934,"stop":2349.772,"duration":6.84},{"text":"There is no provision for the court to be the ultimate arbiter of the controversy?","start":2349.772,"stop":2356.342,"duration":6.57}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan I. Blackman","textObjs":[{"text":"It depends on the issue.","start":2356.342,"stop":2357.611,"duration":1.27},{"text":"The arbitrator will decide the merits, assuming the offer to arbitrate has been accepted according to its terms, which was never done here.","start":2357.611,"stop":2367.734,"duration":10.12},{"text":"After that, depending on the issue, there will or will not be judicial review of some kind, and what this court said as a matter of U.S. law in first options and what all the other countries say, and our brief really was not disputed on that point, is that issues of jurisdiction, whether a contract was ever formed, whether there ever was an agreement to arbitrate is ultimately an issue for a court to independently de novo decide.","start":2367.734,"stop":2397.919,"duration":30.18}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Why are you complaining about the other party not initiating proceedings in the Argentine courts when if you really wanted those proceedings to occur, you could have initiated proceedings in the Argentine courts?","start":2397.919,"stop":2414.78,"duration":16.86}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan I. Blackman","textObjs":[{"text":"First of all, as First Option said, we didn't need to do that.","start":2414.78,"stop":2418.499,"duration":3.72},{"text":"First Option was very clear that it did not require someone who was resisting arbitration and objecting to the arbitrator's jurisdiction, because there is no agreement to run to court.","start":2418.499,"stop":2431.226,"duration":12.73},{"text":"Which would also be very bad policy.","start":2431.226,"stop":2433.092,"duration":1.87},{"text":"We don't want people running to court.","start":2433.092,"stop":2434.861,"duration":1.77},{"text":"We want them to try in -- in arbitration, but subject to judicial review, if the arbitrators get it wrong on the fundamental jurisdictional question.","start":2434.861,"stop":2445.652,"duration":10.79}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"I must say I don't understand that.","start":2445.652,"stop":2447.269,"duration":1.62},{"text":"When -- when you're appealing to a condition for the thing to occur and you can bring that about as -- as readily as the other side, it's -- dog in the manger comes to mind.","start":2447.269,"stop":2460.159,"duration":12.89}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan I. Blackman","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":2460.159,"stop":2460.842,"duration":0.68},{"text":"We weren't the aggrieved party, Justice Scalia.","start":2460.842,"stop":2463.544,"duration":2.7},{"text":"We were not seeking relief.","start":2463.544,"stop":2465.094,"duration":1.55},{"text":"They're the ones who were complaining.","start":2465.094,"stop":2466.996,"duration":1.9},{"text":"We're -- we're the putative defendant, the respondent.","start":2466.996,"stop":2470.448,"duration":3.45},{"text":"There'd be no reason for us to go to court.","start":2470.448,"stop":2473.9,"duration":3.45},{"text":"What our offer to them was, first of all, you have to go to our courts for 18 months.","start":2473.9,"stop":2480.989,"duration":7.09},{"text":"And then it says in A2, and it refers specifically to “ the aforementioned disputes ”, i.e., those disputes that have been brought to our courts,","start":2480.989,"stop":2490.429,"duration":9.44},{"text":"\"those aforementioned disputes can then be arbitrated -- quote -- under the following circumstances. \"","start":2490.429,"stop":2496.265,"duration":5.84},{"text":"And the first of those, in A2 -- Al is waiting the 18 months.","start":2496.265,"stop":2503.186,"duration":6.92},{"text":"And then quite importantly, or in A2(b) the parties can separately agree to arbitrate.","start":2503.186,"stop":2509.673,"duration":6.49},{"text":"Well, if they don't separately agree to arbitrate, which did not occur here, you have to go through A2, Al, which is either wait the 18 months so the local court can try to deal with it -- I'll tell you why that's important in a moment -- or the local court does actually adjudicate it and then the party who's unhappy with that does have the right then, and then only, to go to arbitrate.","start":2509.673,"stop":2536.741,"duration":27.07},{"text":"And that's the temporal sequence that the D.C. Court talked about.","start":2536.741,"stop":2540.627,"duration":3.89},{"text":"It's set forth in the structure of the treaty that the Chief Justice talked about.","start":2540.627,"stop":2545.346,"duration":4.72},{"text":"You go one, two, three.","start":2545.346,"stop":2547.281,"duration":1.93},{"text":"They're in order for a reason.","start":2547.281,"stop":2548.8,"duration":1.52}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"That's the D.C. Circuit treated this as there is no agreement until you go to the local court first.","start":2548.8,"stop":2557.656,"duration":8.86}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan I. Blackman","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":2557.656,"stop":2558.473,"duration":0.82}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"The argument is that there is an agreement to arbitrate.","start":2558.473,"stop":2562.208,"duration":3.74},{"text":"That will be the method of dispute resolution.","start":2562.208,"stop":2564.393,"duration":2.18},{"text":"You have to take certain steps before.","start":2564.393,"stop":2567.612,"duration":3.22},{"text":"So, you have to go to the local court.","start":2567.612,"stop":2573.333,"duration":5.72},{"text":"But why isn't the dispute settlement mechanism decided upon by the parties' arbitration, and then what you have to do before that is in the nature of a procedural condition?","start":2573.333,"stop":2590.46,"duration":17.13}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan I. Blackman","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't -- I don't think that's the correct analysis, Justice Ginsburg, because the dispute resolution mechanism which is, again, is an offer made by two States to each other to--","start":2590.46,"stop":2602.018,"duration":11.56}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Blackman, can I just ask you to assume for a second that that's not so.","start":2602.018,"stop":2605.654,"duration":3.64},{"text":"If you had -- if BG and the Republic of Argentina had itself entered into this agreement, would you agree that this is a typical Howsam kind of provision?","start":2605.654,"stop":2618.295,"duration":12.64}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan I. Blackman","textObjs":[{"text":"--I would actually not, Your Honor.","start":2618.295,"stop":2620.246,"duration":1.95},{"text":"Howsam -- let's talk about the facts of Howsam.","start":2620.246,"stop":2623.031,"duration":2.78},{"text":"Howsam was -- there was no dispute that there was a contract between the Howsams and the broker/dealer to arbitrate under the NASD rules.","start":2623.031,"stop":2632.221,"duration":9.19},{"text":"Those NASD rules themselves contained an eligibility requirement that the claim can't be more than six years old.","start":2632.221,"stop":2638.958,"duration":6.74},{"text":"And those same rules also said the arbitrators get to decide about the interpretation and application of our rules.","start":2638.958,"stop":2646.381,"duration":7.42},{"text":"So it was a classic situation--","start":2646.381,"stop":2648.364,"duration":1.98}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"So how do you -- how do you distinguish John Wiley, which I think--","start":2648.364,"stop":2651.449,"duration":3.09}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan I. Blackman","textObjs":[{"text":"--John Wiley--","start":2651.449,"stop":2652.035,"duration":0.59}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"--has two components and the second cuts against you.","start":2652.035,"stop":2654.835,"duration":2.8}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan I. Blackman","textObjs":[{"text":"--And the first cuts in our favor, Justice Sotomayor.","start":2654.835,"stop":2657.37,"duration":2.53},{"text":"That's exactly right.","start":2657.37,"stop":2658.371,"duration":1},{"text":"My friend kept talking about John Wiley as involving only issues of procedural preconditions.","start":2658.371,"stop":2665.792,"duration":7.42},{"text":"But the first part of John Wiley where the Court says quite clearly, you have independent judicial review, has to do with whether there is an agreement to arbitrate at all between the parties.","start":2665.792,"stop":2679.952,"duration":14.16},{"text":"In that case, the parties sought to be pulled into arbitration against its will was a successor and the issue which the Court independently decided was, is that successor a party.","start":2679.952,"stop":2691.926,"duration":11.97}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"Everybody's getting to the same question, I think, but I haven't quite heard the answer.","start":2691.926,"stop":2697.08,"duration":5.15},{"text":"Of course, you're right in many countries.","start":2697.08,"stop":2699.681,"duration":2.6},{"text":"The question of arbitrability, that is to say, is there a contract is for the Court.","start":2699.681,"stop":2704.749,"duration":5.07},{"text":"In an investment treaty, I can find a lot of authority that says whether this counts as an investment is a matter for the Court.","start":2704.749,"stop":2712.339,"duration":7.59},{"text":"But the question in front of us, is this that kind of decision?","start":2712.339,"stop":2717.476,"duration":5.14},{"text":"Is it one for the Court?","start":2717.476,"stop":2719.243,"duration":1.77},{"text":"Or is it one for the arbitrator?","start":2719.243,"stop":2721.36,"duration":2.12},{"text":"And to just summarize why it might be for the arbitrator, A, it's procedural but that's not sufficient.","start":2721.36,"stop":2727.081,"duration":5.72},{"text":"B, it refers to UNC -- whatever it is -- UNCITRAL?","start":2727.081,"stop":2732.152,"duration":5.07}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan I. Blackman","textObjs":[{"text":"UNCITRAL.","start":2732.152,"stop":2732.752,"duration":0.6}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2732.752,"stop":2733.268,"duration":0.52},{"text":"It refers to their rules.","start":2733.268,"stop":2734.802,"duration":1.53},{"text":"Their rules provide all matters of competence over the arbitrator.","start":2734.802,"stop":2738.906,"duration":4.1},{"text":"The scholars have done exhaustive work saying most countries think that.","start":2738.906,"stop":2743.041,"duration":4.14},{"text":"The Doctrine of Competence-Competence goes further.","start":2743.041,"stop":2745.993,"duration":2.95},{"text":"And you also have the AAA rules which say the same thing.","start":2745.993,"stop":2750.211,"duration":4.22},{"text":"So those are all against you.","start":2750.211,"stop":2751.728,"duration":1.52},{"text":"For you is the position of the -- the item in the document, first and foremost.","start":2751.728,"stop":2758.901,"duration":7.17},{"text":"All right.","start":2758.901,"stop":2759.684,"duration":0.78},{"text":"I'm trying to summarize what I've got as the arguments for and against.","start":2759.684,"stop":2762.953,"duration":3.27},{"text":"Now, what do you say to make me think there's even more for--","start":2762.953,"stop":2765.82,"duration":2.87}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan I. Blackman","textObjs":[{"text":"I agree with you.","start":2765.82,"stop":2766.504,"duration":0.68},{"text":"The text is key and the text controls.","start":2766.504,"stop":2768.589,"duration":2.09},{"text":"However, I strongly disagree, with all respect, to your statements about competence-competence and what other countries do, because we have shown essentially without dispute here, and this in the third restatement and it's in the case law of all these other countries that competence-competence or competence-competence, or if you say it in German with a K, all that means is the arbitrators get the first crack--","start":2768.589,"stop":2794.49,"duration":25.9}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"--So I agree that's not--","start":2794.49,"stop":2795.64,"duration":1.15}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan I. Blackman","textObjs":[{"text":"--it's not the last word.","start":2795.64,"stop":2796.692,"duration":1.05}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"--But those are not relevant.","start":2796.692,"stop":2798.125,"duration":1.43},{"text":"I mean, those are relevant.","start":2798.125,"stop":2799.342,"duration":1.22},{"text":"I'm saying they would farther.","start":2799.342,"stop":2800.744,"duration":1.4},{"text":"And I think in what I've seen so far, it gives on certain kinds of procedural gateway questions, deference to the arbitrator, which is what is at issue here.","start":2800.744,"stop":2812.885,"duration":12.14},{"text":"And now -- now I'm back to the same question.","start":2812.885,"stop":2815.837,"duration":2.95},{"text":"What is your evidence from this contract that this is not the kind of gateway question that is for the arbitrator?","start":2815.837,"stop":2822.923,"duration":7.09}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan I. Blackman","textObjs":[{"text":"This is -- and, again, my friend conceded this -- this is an offer to a unilateral contract.","start":2822.923,"stop":2829.094,"duration":6.17},{"text":"How does a unilateral contract get formed?","start":2829.094,"stop":2831.996,"duration":2.9},{"text":"Here we're back at our basic contract formation principle.","start":2831.996,"stop":2836,"duration":4}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't think he conceded it.","start":2836,"stop":2836.95,"duration":0.95},{"text":"He conceded that that was your argument.","start":2836.95,"stop":2838.685,"duration":1.74}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan I. Blackman","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that I misheard.","start":2838.685,"stop":2840.368,"duration":1.68},{"text":"[Laughter]","start":2840.368,"stop":2840.751,"duration":0.38}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"There's a subtle difference between the two.","start":2840.751,"stop":2842.403,"duration":1.65},{"text":"[Laughter]","start":2842.403,"stop":2842.669,"duration":0.27}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan I. Blackman","textObjs":[{"text":"I misheard him.","start":2842.669,"stop":2843.036,"duration":0.37},{"text":"I misheard him then, and I apologize, Justice Scalia.","start":2843.036,"stop":2845.855,"duration":2.82},{"text":"But this is, in fact, if you apply ordinary contract formation principles, as the Court says you must do in First Options and in Granite Rock, if you apply those principles, this is classic offer.","start":2845.855,"stop":2859.429,"duration":13.57},{"text":"And the offer, we all know, has to be met by an acceptance on those terms, not on other terms.","start":2859.429,"stop":2865.182,"duration":5.75}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, you said a few minutes ago you were going to explain why this litigation requirement is important.","start":2865.182,"stop":2871.753,"duration":6.57},{"text":"And that is important to me because I don't see what it accomplishes.","start":2871.753,"stop":2876.307,"duration":4.55},{"text":"I can understand a waiting period, but this is more than a waiting period.","start":2876.307,"stop":2879.776,"duration":3.47},{"text":"You have a party who doesn't want to litigate in the -- in the courts of Argentina.","start":2879.776,"stop":2883.394,"duration":3.62},{"text":"It doesn't think it's going to get a fair shake there.","start":2883.394,"stop":2885.246,"duration":1.85},{"text":"What is the point of requiring this -- now, I understand, it's a requirement.","start":2885.246,"stop":2891.65,"duration":6.4},{"text":"But if it's not very important, if it isn't going to achieve anything, that seems to me to weigh against the conclusion that it's a -- that it is a condition of consent.","start":2891.65,"stop":2900.523,"duration":8.87}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan I. Blackman","textObjs":[{"text":"It is very important.","start":2900.523,"stop":2902.375,"duration":1.85},{"text":"First of all as a factual matter, this type of requirement appears in about 8 percent of bids and it is most prevalent in UK bids.","start":2902.375,"stop":2911.147,"duration":8.77},{"text":"So this is not some weird Argentine thing.","start":2911.147,"stop":2913.499,"duration":2.35},{"text":"The UK thinks this is important.","start":2913.499,"stop":2915.165,"duration":1.67},{"text":"Why?","start":2915.165,"stop":2915.949,"duration":0.78},{"text":"A number of reasons.","start":2915.949,"stop":2917.284,"duration":1.34},{"text":"First of all, a lot of these investment disputes, in fact, the vast majority, involve challenge to some local law, some local regulation.","start":2917.284,"stop":2926.157,"duration":8.87},{"text":"And you want to have the local court have the first look at construing it, just as you would construe a statute before you reach the constitutional question.","start":2926.157,"stop":2935.679,"duration":9.52},{"text":"The local court can illuminate the dispute, the investment treaty dispute by saying what does our law actually mean?","start":2935.679,"stop":2943.701,"duration":8.02},{"text":"Is our law legal under our Constitution?","start":2943.701,"stop":2947.753,"duration":4.05},{"text":"That's one thing.","start":2947.753,"stop":2949.355,"duration":1.6},{"text":"That's very important.","start":2949.355,"stop":2950.155,"duration":0.8}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Let me just interrupt before -- before the time expires.","start":2950.155,"stop":2952.64,"duration":2.48},{"text":"But I don't understand -- I don't know what the procedure is in Argentina.","start":2952.64,"stop":2955.326,"duration":2.69},{"text":"Let's assume their civil procedure is like ours.","start":2955.326,"stop":2957.611,"duration":2.28},{"text":"So you say they have to file a complaint.","start":2957.611,"stop":2960.428,"duration":2.82},{"text":"All right.","start":2960.428,"stop":2960.763,"duration":0.34},{"text":"They file a one-page complaint.","start":2960.763,"stop":2962.196,"duration":1.43},{"text":"They do the minimal necessary to keep the case alive in court.","start":2962.196,"stop":2966.384,"duration":4.19},{"text":"Maybe they don't even do that, because they don't care; they don't want the thing to be -- to be decided.","start":2966.384,"stop":2971.702,"duration":5.32},{"text":"All they're doing is running out the 18 months.","start":2971.702,"stop":2974.404,"duration":2.7},{"text":"What is achieved by that?","start":2974.404,"stop":2976.173,"duration":1.77}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan I. Blackman","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, but that's their choice, which they, in fact, made here not to avail themselves of the procedure--","start":2976.173,"stop":2982.41,"duration":6.24}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, let's say they avail themselves of the procedure in only the most perfunctory way so as to satisfy the 18-month requirement.","start":2982.41,"stop":2990.665,"duration":8.26},{"text":"But not for the purpose--","start":2990.665,"stop":2991.615,"duration":0.95}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan I. Blackman","textObjs":[{"text":"--Why should my client be punished because they don't diligently pursue a requirement of our offer.","start":2991.615,"stop":2997.853,"duration":6.24},{"text":"They say actually in their brief in one sentence, we accepted the offer and in the next sentence virtually--","start":2997.853,"stop":3004.423,"duration":6.57}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--You're really -- you're not answering--","start":3004.423,"stop":3004.925,"duration":0.5}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan I. Blackman","textObjs":[{"text":"--they say we elected not to follow--","start":3004.925,"stop":3006.559,"duration":1.63}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Could you finish your answer.","start":3006.559,"stop":3008.159,"duration":1.6}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--You're not answering my question.","start":3008.159,"stop":3009.511,"duration":1.35},{"text":"What is -- if they do not litigate the matter in -- in such a way as to get a decision on any of these local law issues, they just keep it alive perfunctorily for 18 months, what is achieved by that?","start":3009.511,"stop":3024.437,"duration":14.93}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan I. Blackman","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, they have -- well, they've complied with it.","start":3024.437,"stop":3027.472,"duration":3.04},{"text":"But more importantly, it's what could be achieved if they wanted to achieve something, which is, as I said before, constructions of local law that would bear on the investment dispute.","start":3027.472,"stop":3039.446,"duration":11.97},{"text":"That's important.","start":3039.446,"stop":3040.18,"duration":0.73},{"text":"Narrowing issues, making determinations which are not binding, but which are nonetheless perhaps instructive and helpful to the arbitrators.","start":3040.18,"stop":3050.252,"duration":10.07},{"text":"That's another issue.","start":3050.252,"stop":3051.088,"duration":0.84},{"text":"Settlement is another issue.","start":3051.088,"stop":3053.956,"duration":2.87},{"text":"We talked about waiting.","start":3053.956,"stop":3055.356,"duration":1.4},{"text":"We have EEOC.","start":3055.356,"stop":3056.54,"duration":1.18},{"text":"You first have to go to the -- to the commission because this sometimes gets settled.","start":3056.54,"stop":3062.144,"duration":5.6},{"text":"If it doesn't get settled, as I say, it can be narrowed.","start":3062.144,"stop":3067.798,"duration":5.65},{"text":"All kinds of things that would be helpful to an ultimate arbitration.","start":3067.798,"stop":3072.851,"duration":5.05},{"text":"And they could win, by the way.","start":3072.851,"stop":3074.134,"duration":1.28},{"text":"They could win.","start":3074.134,"stop":3075.119,"duration":0.99}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Blackman, could you sort of indulge an assumption for me?","start":3075.119,"stop":3077.821,"duration":2.7},{"text":"And the assumption is that if this provision were in an agreement between two parties, we would treat it as a Howsam-John Wiley kind of provision; in other words, we would say that this is just a procedural rule.","start":3077.821,"stop":3093.515,"duration":15.69},{"text":"That's the side of the line it falls on.","start":3093.515,"stop":3096.3,"duration":2.79},{"text":"So my question to you is: Why should this be any different?","start":3096.3,"stop":3100.269,"duration":3.97},{"text":"You're treating yourself as though you never made an agreement.","start":3100.269,"stop":3104.389,"duration":4.12},{"text":"But, in fact, you did make an important agreement.","start":3104.389,"stop":3106.925,"duration":2.54},{"text":"You made an agreement with the U.K., the entire point and purpose of which was to allow U.K. citizens to bring certain kinds of disputes before an arbitrator.","start":3106.925,"stop":3117.48,"duration":10.55},{"text":"So once we have a U.K. citizen with the right kind of dispute, it seems to me you're just in the position of any other person who's agreed to this provision.","start":3117.48,"stop":3127.169,"duration":9.69},{"text":"And in -- in my assumption, if it's a John Wiley type provision, it should go to an arbitrator.","start":3127.169,"stop":3133.575,"duration":6.41}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan I. Blackman","textObjs":[{"text":"I have a number of responses to that, Justice Kagan.","start":3133.575,"stop":3136.777,"duration":3.2},{"text":"First of all, I don't think it is just a John Wiley sort of--","start":3136.777,"stop":3141.679,"duration":4.9}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"I know.","start":3141.679,"stop":3141.979,"duration":0.3},{"text":"But I said just assume that for me.","start":3141.979,"stop":3143.631,"duration":1.65},{"text":"And tell me why you are in a position where some other result should go into effect.","start":3143.631,"stop":3151.386,"duration":7.76}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan I. Blackman","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, it's kind of assuming the conclusion if this is just John Wiley, that's a hard case for us.","start":3151.386,"stop":3158.123,"duration":6.74},{"text":"But the structure of the treaty, with all respect, demonstrates it's not.","start":3158.123,"stop":3163.427,"duration":5.3},{"text":"And that would be true even if this was, in fact, a contract between us and BG.","start":3163.427,"stop":3170.098,"duration":6.67},{"text":"If we had a contract with BG that says you have to sue us first, okay, and then after 18 months, you can arbitrate with us, I don't think we would just assume that that translates into you have to arbitrate with us.","start":3170.098,"stop":3183.925,"duration":13.83},{"text":"They're really suggesting here, Justice Kagan, that this elaborate provision boils down to Argentina promises to arbitrate all investment disputes with BG.","start":3183.925,"stop":3194.563,"duration":10.64},{"text":"That's what it says.","start":3194.563,"stop":3195.146,"duration":0.58}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the problem is--","start":3195.146,"stop":3195.829,"duration":0.68}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"Please.","start":3195.829,"stop":3197.046,"duration":1.22}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--You're -- it's a point on which I'm regularly confused.","start":3197.046,"stop":3201.9,"duration":4.85},{"text":"You just said if we had this provision in a contract with -- a private contract that said you must sue us, but there you have already a formed separate agreement to arbitrate.","start":3201.9,"stop":3211.023,"duration":9.12},{"text":"And it seems to me clear that those, what do you call them, preconditions or whatever, that that -- the argument that that's for the arbitrator to decide.","start":3211.023,"stop":3218.511,"duration":7.49},{"text":"They may well decide that, you know, you didn't comply so you don't get to arbitrate.","start":3218.511,"stop":3222.23,"duration":3.72},{"text":"But it seems to me, typically, under First Options and Howsam that is for the arbitrator.","start":3222.23,"stop":3227.634,"duration":5.4},{"text":"Now, what makes it distinct in your case?","start":3227.634,"stop":3230.669,"duration":3.03},{"text":"What, is it just the order that they're in or what?","start":3230.669,"stop":3235.304,"duration":4.64},{"text":"Or is it something special about a sovereign's agreement?","start":3235.304,"stop":3238.506,"duration":3.2}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan I. Blackman","textObjs":[{"text":"It's -- it's kind of all of the above.","start":3238.506,"stop":3241.292,"duration":2.79},{"text":"It's the text, the fact that it is, in fact, an offer by a sovereign rather than an originally bilateral agreement with the private party.","start":3241.292,"stop":3251.316,"duration":10.02},{"text":"But it's also -- and this is much of what the case hinges on, is this an issue of contract formation.","start":3251.316,"stop":3258.253,"duration":6.94},{"text":"If it's an offer, it has to be accepted on its terms.","start":3258.253,"stop":3261.455,"duration":3.2},{"text":"And those are formation issues that go into construing an existing agreement.","start":3261.455,"stop":3268.042,"duration":6.59}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"It all gets down to the question, how do we tell, you know, the contract formation from the blue paper, right?","start":3268.042,"stop":3274.363,"duration":6.32},{"text":"I mean, if it says, you know, we agree to arbitrate and we use these rules and those rules say you have to have it on blue paper and it's not on blue paper, they say, oh, we didn't agree to have it not on blue paper.","start":3274.363,"stop":3283.384,"duration":9.02},{"text":"How do we distinguish between those two scenarios?","start":3283.384,"stop":3289.038,"duration":5.65}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan I. Blackman","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I think you have to kind of look at the language.","start":3289.038,"stop":3293.84,"duration":4.8},{"text":"And here, with all respect, it was clear to the circuit.","start":3293.84,"stop":3296.359,"duration":2.52},{"text":"I think it's -- we think it's clear that the consent, which remember, absent which there would be no arbitration, this is a sovereign, going back to sovereign immunity in our earlier case.","start":3296.359,"stop":3307.934,"duration":11.58},{"text":"Where consent is expressly put -- the word “ consent ” is not used -- but the clear language of the text and the implications to be drawn from it clearly show that the sovereign is not willing to arbitrate absent the 18-months' recourse to its courts, you should view that as a condition precedent to a unilateral contract that must be accepted by action.","start":3307.934,"stop":3337.203,"duration":29.27},{"text":"And the action is to bring this suit in the local court and wait 18 months.","start":3337.203,"stop":3343.09,"duration":5.89},{"text":"An analogy, which may not be helpful, but I thought of it.","start":3343.09,"stop":3346.309,"duration":3.22},{"text":"So I'll give it to you.","start":3346.309,"stop":3347.227,"duration":0.92},{"text":"If I'm looking for someone to paint my house and I make an offer to him, I say, I'll hire you to do it if you post the bond.","start":3347.227,"stop":3355.917,"duration":8.69},{"text":"That's an offer to the unilateral contract.","start":3355.917,"stop":3357.917,"duration":2},{"text":"He has to post the bond.","start":3357.917,"stop":3359.385,"duration":1.47},{"text":"He can't say, you know, I really don't like the bond or you want a $20,000 bond, which isn't my offer, but I'll give you ten, now we have a contract.","start":3359.385,"stop":3367.824,"duration":8.44},{"text":"But let's assume we now make the contract and I have progress payments in the contract.","start":3367.824,"stop":3373.961,"duration":6.14},{"text":"Now we have a signed agreement between us that says, I'll pay you, you know, $10,000 per floor.","start":3373.961,"stop":3381.732,"duration":7.77},{"text":"That's the kind of condition precedent within the contract that Howsam, perhaps, addresses.","start":3381.732,"stop":3387.969,"duration":6.24},{"text":"But the first one is the formation issue that First Options addresses, did the Kaplans ever make the contract?","start":3387.969,"stop":3394.792,"duration":6.82}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what would happen -- what would happen in this case if there was a judge's strike, so none of the courts were operating in Argentina?","start":3394.792,"stop":3402.229,"duration":7.44},{"text":"What would happen then?","start":3402.229,"stop":3404.763,"duration":2.53}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan I. Blackman","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, all you have to do is actually file.","start":3404.763,"stop":3408.299,"duration":3.54},{"text":"So even if the courts weren't operating, which is an extreme hypothetical, all you need to do is file and wait the 18 months.","start":3408.299,"stop":3415.721,"duration":7.42}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"No, but the clerk's office is closed.","start":3415.721,"stop":3417.055,"duration":1.33}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan I. Blackman","textObjs":[{"text":"The clerk's office is closed, too?","start":3417.055,"stop":3418.757,"duration":1.7},{"text":"[Laughter]","start":3418.757,"stop":3419.423,"duration":0.67},{"text":"I suspect that the -- there would be a very strong case to be made to the arbitrators that if the claimant, unlike here, did everything it could to comply, and here remember, the claimant deliberately, quote “ elected not to comply ”, the arbitrators might well find that the condition was excused and a reviewing--","start":3419.423,"stop":3439.504,"duration":20.08}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"No, you can't -- no, you can't say that.","start":3439.504,"stop":3441.321,"duration":1.82},{"text":"You can't say that.","start":3441.321,"stop":3442.373,"duration":1.05},{"text":"There is no arbitration agreement under your -- it would still be for the court.","start":3442.373,"stop":3446.507,"duration":4.13}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan I. Blackman","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, there could be an arbitration in the first instance.","start":3446.507,"stop":3447.84,"duration":1.33}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"Your -- your whole argument gives me intellectual whiplash.","start":3447.84,"stop":3450.126,"duration":2.29},{"text":"You have to say--","start":3450.126,"stop":3450.909,"duration":0.78},{"text":"[Laughter]","start":3450.909,"stop":3451.644,"duration":0.73},{"text":"--well, you have to -- you have to go first to the court, because that's what the arbitration mechanism provides, but there's no arbitration mechanism.","start":3451.644,"stop":3459.332,"duration":7.69}]},{"speakerName":"Jonathan I. Blackman","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":3459.332,"stop":3460.167,"duration":0.84},{"text":"But in this case what would happen would be what happened in First Options and often happens, one party invokes arbitration and the other party says, I never agreed to arbitrate with you.","start":3460.167,"stop":3469.956,"duration":9.79},{"text":"It would be very imprudent for the defendant in that case to do nothing and default.","start":3469.956,"stop":3474.758,"duration":4.8},{"text":"And you said in First Options specifically, you don't need to do that.","start":3474.758,"stop":3478.212,"duration":3.45},{"text":"So you present the issue to the arbitrators and you would then argue that there's no agreement and the arbitrators would say, well, there is an agreement or a condition was excused.","start":3478.212,"stop":3487.834,"duration":9.62},{"text":"And ultimately, on judicial review, on your facts, undoubtedly a court would be likely to find, well, of course, they did their best.","start":3487.834,"stop":3495.005,"duration":7.17},{"text":"They tried to comply with a condition.","start":3495.005,"stop":3496.607,"duration":1.6},{"text":"But that doesn't affect, to use my friend's terminology, the question presented, which is who decides in the first instance and then finally.","start":3496.607,"stop":3504.863,"duration":8.26}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, counsel.","start":3504.863,"stop":3505.646,"duration":0.78},{"text":"Mr. Goldstein, five minutes.","start":3505.646,"stop":3507.096,"duration":1.45}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Goldstein","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, I do have a rule that distinguishes the A4 paper and that rule should be, and we think it does follow from the analysis of Howsam, which is just a thinking about when people make agreements and what they expect is that an arbitration agreement is formed and a party consents to arbitration when they guarantee that the ultimate decision can be made by an arbitrator and not a court.","start":3507.096,"stop":3530.778,"duration":23.68},{"text":"It's form selection.","start":3530.778,"stop":3531.696,"duration":0.92},{"text":"We're going to have the ultimate decision made by the arbitrator.","start":3531.696,"stop":3533.882,"duration":2.19},{"text":"And that rule is applied in the investment treaty context as follows.","start":3533.882,"stop":3537.1,"duration":3.22},{"text":"And it is, there is consent to arbitration when the investor is guaranteed that their claim can ultimately be decided by a court and the State can't force it to be ultimately -- excuse me -- by an arbitrator, and the State can't force it to ultimately be decided by a court.","start":3537.1,"stop":3552.094,"duration":14.99},{"text":"And I'll show you where that rule, how that line is divided in this treaty.","start":3552.094,"stop":3556.662,"duration":4.57},{"text":"And that is, I gave you the three conditions at the beginning.","start":3556.662,"stop":3559.278,"duration":2.62},{"text":"Those are not A4 paper.","start":3559.278,"stop":3560.697,"duration":1.42},{"text":"You have to be a U.K. investor, you have to have a treaty claim, you have to be suing another party to the treaty.","start":3560.697,"stop":3569.235,"duration":8.54},{"text":"And if those aren't true, then there is no arbitration agreement and Argentina has every reason to say I have no idea why these arbitrators are here, this person's from Ecuador, not from the United Kingdom.","start":3569.235,"stop":3579.091,"duration":9.86},{"text":"But at that point, once we are a U.K. investor and we have invested in Argentina, that's the performance that is required, once we did that, then we are protected by Article 8, the dispute resolution provision.","start":3579.091,"stop":3591.399,"duration":12.31},{"text":"And you look at Article 8 and you, okay, does that guarantee that you have the right to ultimately have it decided by the arbitrators, or can Argentina actually insist that it will be ultimately decided by a court.","start":3591.399,"stop":3602.12,"duration":10.72},{"text":"And it's the former.","start":3602.12,"stop":3602.956,"duration":0.84},{"text":"We made clear, I think, and nobody disagrees, that they can't force us to go into court and wait for that ruling, take that ruling in any way, shape, or form.","start":3602.956,"stop":3612.162,"duration":9.21},{"text":"Now my friend says that, look, this is like a unilateral agreement, and this is like where I say I'll hire you to paint my house if you post a bond.","start":3612.162,"stop":3622.351,"duration":10.19},{"text":"Well, that is a terrible argument for them because this treaty reads as if he was saying, I'll let you paint my house if you post the bond or I post the bond.","start":3622.351,"stop":3630.29,"duration":7.94},{"text":"Because, remember, the thing they want us to perform on, supposedly, is something they can do, too.","start":3630.29,"stop":3635.009,"duration":4.72},{"text":"Who ever heard of unilateral agreement that was conditioned on either party doing something?","start":3635.009,"stop":3640.562,"duration":5.55}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"They say that only the complaining party can bring a lawsuit.","start":3640.562,"stop":3645.466,"duration":4.9},{"text":"Evidently they have no declaratory judgment procedure in Argentina.","start":3645.466,"stop":3649.937,"duration":4.47}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Goldstein","textObjs":[{"text":"That, I don't believe that is correct, Justice Scalia.","start":3649.937,"stop":3652.403,"duration":2.47}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"I was going to ask them that.","start":3652.403,"stop":3654.072,"duration":1.67}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Goldstein","textObjs":[{"text":"I see.","start":3654.072,"stop":3654.522,"duration":0.45},{"text":"I believe the answer, when this was put to them, his answer to your question was I just don't have to do that.","start":3654.522,"stop":3660.743,"duration":6.22},{"text":"His view was, and it's a perfectly fine position to take, and that is he's not going to help me win my case.","start":3660.743,"stop":3665.797,"duration":5.05},{"text":"Fine.","start":3665.797,"stop":3666.397,"duration":0.6},{"text":"But it does describe whether this is a condition of consent, that he could do it too.","start":3666.397,"stop":3672.132,"duration":5.74},{"text":"And if he could do it too, it can't be something that he is waiting for me to perform on at all.","start":3672.132,"stop":3676.003,"duration":3.87},{"text":"I would say that on this question of whether it has any value, that all that you got, Justice Alito, was that if I were to pursue the case in the Argentine courts maybe something would happen, we might learn a little about Argentine law.","start":3676.003,"stop":3688.326,"duration":12.32},{"text":"First thing's first.","start":3688.326,"stop":3689.677,"duration":1.35},{"text":"I don't have to pursue it.","start":3689.677,"stop":3690.945,"duration":1.27},{"text":"Remember, his whole point is, when asked if the courts were closed, said I just have to put the piece of paper down.","start":3690.945,"stop":3695.747,"duration":4.8},{"text":"So if this were a treaty provision that actually involved litigation, involved exhaustion of remedies where we might learn something that might be a different case.","start":3695.747,"stop":3703.436,"duration":7.69},{"text":"But this is a waiting period in an Argentine court.","start":3703.436,"stop":3706.455,"duration":3.02},{"text":"And remember as well, these are treaty claims and it is perfectly clear and undisputed that the local court, even if it decided the treaty claims, their agreement would not bind the arbitrators.","start":3706.455,"stop":3717.677,"duration":11.22},{"text":"And so he says, well, hey, we might win.","start":3717.677,"stop":3719.277,"duration":1.6}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm not so sure you don't have to do anything, you can just submit the paper.","start":3719.277,"stop":3723.262,"duration":3.99},{"text":"It says you have to submit it to the decision of the competent tribunal.","start":3723.262,"stop":3726.783,"duration":3.52},{"text":"And if the submission requires, okay, now you have to file your brief, and you say, I'm not going to, I'm not sure that you've submitted it to a tribunal for its decision.","start":3726.783,"stop":3734.886,"duration":8.1}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Goldstein","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Mr. Chief Justice, I would then say that's a possible argument.","start":3734.886,"stop":3738.506,"duration":3.62},{"text":"But let's figure out who we would ordinary expect to figure that out.","start":3738.506,"stop":3741.958,"duration":3.45},{"text":"This is a treaty provision.","start":3741.958,"stop":3743.158,"duration":1.2},{"text":"It's the experts involved in treaty interpretation, are the three neutral arbitrators, who really do this every day.","start":3743.158,"stop":3749.646,"duration":6.49},{"text":"It's what they do.","start":3749.646,"stop":3750.414,"duration":0.77},{"text":"They have enormous expertise in interpreting treaties.","start":3750.414,"stop":3752.798,"duration":2.38},{"text":"And so you might say, and it would be a perfectly valid interpretation, well, maybe submitting it to the local court requires some activity.","start":3752.798,"stop":3758.835,"duration":6.04},{"text":"But do we really expect when the U.K. and Argentina ended this treaty, that it would actually be the Supreme Court of the United States that would be deciding that question, or instead, the arbitrators.","start":3758.835,"stop":3769.81,"duration":10.97},{"text":"And if you believe it's the arbitrators then we win, because it's the kind of procedural question that we put to them purposely.","start":3769.81,"stop":3775.463,"duration":5.65}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That seems that you're not totally circular in begging the question.","start":3775.463,"stop":3778.065,"duration":2.6},{"text":"I don't know that a sovereign would be anxious to submit its sovereignty to three international law experts.","start":3778.065,"stop":3785.402,"duration":7.34}]},{"speakerName":"Thomas Goldstein","textObjs":[{"text":"And surely they wouldn't, Mr. Chief Justice, but that's the point of the treaty.","start":3785.402,"stop":3789.273,"duration":3.87},{"text":"Remember my friend said, look, if it weren't for this treaty we could never sue them.","start":3789.273,"stop":3793.675,"duration":4.4},{"text":"That's the reason there's the treaty because if there wasn't the treaty and we couldn't get relief from them, we would have never invested.","start":3793.675,"stop":3799.829,"duration":6.15},{"text":"And so the whole point of this treaty is to put these disputes into arbitration.","start":3799.829,"stop":3804.216,"duration":4.39},{"text":"There is no special substantive rights in this treaty.","start":3804.216,"stop":3807.168,"duration":2.95},{"text":"They are all customary international law.","start":3807.168,"stop":3808.801,"duration":1.63},{"text":"The thing that matters in this treaty, the thing that matters in all the treaties is I don't have to have my case decided by an Argentine court.","start":3808.801,"stop":3816.09,"duration":7.29}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, counsel.","start":3816.09,"stop":3817.623,"duration":1.53},{"text":"The case is submitted.","start":3817.623,"stop":3818.806,"duration":1.18}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Roberts Court","arguedOn":"Dec 2, 2013","petitioner":"BG Group PLC","respondent":"Republic of Argentina","docket":"12-138","citation":"572 US _ (2014)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/572/12-138","lowerCourt":"","grantedOn":"Jun 10, 2013","decidedOn":"Mar 5, 2014"}